title: HyperCube EVO Z bracket for POM anti backlash nut
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
The default mounting bracket houses a 10 mm (at the hub, 22 mm at the flange) trapezoidal nut, the POM anti-backlash nut I received is considerable larger (20 mm at the hub, flange is about 36.5 mm), therefore I have redrawn the original mount to house this larger nut and kept the same center of the original nut. Note this nut only has 2 holes to fasten the nut.

Used anti-backlash nut is https://www.aliexpress.com/item/1pcs-TR8-8-eliminate-clearance-nut-anti-backlash-nut-pom-polyurethane-PU-nut-trapezoidal-screw-nut/32518758192.html?spm=a2g0s.9042311.0.0.hPsjNl. A sketch of the dimensions is added. Note that I created an OpenSCAD model for this nut. You can find this here: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2634333. Note that I have created a similar anti-backlash-nut (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2634333) and an improved version of the nut (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2649952) to print yourself in nylon or POM.

The bracket design is created in OpenSCAD which allows for simple and fast adjustments of the model. An STL file has been provided as an example but I encourage everyone to build their own STL.

Edit 20/11/2017:
Uploaded version 2, fixed some small issues. Updated the text to include links to print-yourself backlash nut designs

title: Filament rod brackets for vertical mounting on table legs
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This bracket setup is made to go on the legs of a table based on a 2x4 homebuilt table. The filament will protrude from under the table and it will accomodate up to a 1 inch rod which will easily lift out for easy filament replacements.  
The brackets are 1 inch in thickness and 4 inches in height at the back tapering to 2 inch at the front. Each side has 1/2 inch of area for the rod to rest in.  
The top and bottom side have 1/4 inch holes for secure mounting to the wooden legs of the table. I used the part to predrill the holes so the angle would be right and the bracket would mount flush. Placing a large flat washer under the head of the 1/4 mounting screw should make the mount VERY secure.  
It is a good strong bracket and should support your filament well

description.text: Saw some variable ratio drive mechanism that made me think of this. Figuring out how to have variable radius drive pins wasn't too hard, but figuring out how to vary the radius of the circles they engage into seems to be a stumbling block. (Circles are actually a set radius which is based on an epicyclic drive, but the offset from center has to vary in the same way as the pin offset.) However even if that's worked out it wouldn't be a true cycloidal drive as the outer engagement surface wouldn't be to a fixed or geared type ratio, so it'd require a friction ring to allow some minor slip. (Basically a rubber tire of sorts.) Thus the "quasi" aspect of the name since it's not quite a true cycloidal drive. Also still some other parts to work out anyways, just a rough-idea thing for a mechanism.

title: Dr Boo's Astounding Magnetic Shoelaces
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
While magnetic shoelaces are hardly new, this rethink provides an extremely strong magnetic latching shoelace that practically prevents accidental un-tying. These are strong in both the horizontal and vertical directions - I simply cannot pull them apart "accidentally" no matter how hard I try. A small tab is provided at the edge of the latch which makes it very simple to lift and detach. The mechanism works by using the magnet attraction to hold the parts together, and a ridge/trench mechanism to prevent lateral movement. These work together to hold the mechanism rigid during use and prevent accidental detachment of the laces. You will require 4x neodymium magnets, size 20mm x 10mm x 2mm to glue into the recesses - make sure you get the polarity right!

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aQhvi6FXR-8&feature=youtu.be

You need to print two of the STL object - glue in the magnets, and then lace into your shoes like shown in the picture. The picture is an earlier prototype with 4 holes - there are three in the model provided, giving better spacing.

Per request, this is a globe of the planet Mars.  The primary file (marsglobeexag2.stl - printed in natural ABS) is vertically exaggerated about 50X.  The other file (marsglobeexag.stl - printed in silver ABS) is only exagerrated about 10X.  If you print it large the less exaggerated one would be suitable for painting and display, but for my purposes (a tactile model for bringing space science to the blind) the more exaggerated is my choice. Olympia Mons looks like a nipple and Valis Marineris almost cuts through the shell.

This is not a derivative, but a serious tip of the hat to tbuser for his Mars Surface Map (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:25319) as I used the same altimetry source data for the heightfield, which was then attached to a sphere (radius = width of heightfield/2*pi and aligned under the heightfield mesh) using the ApplyMeshUVN command in Rhino3D. To get the differences in vertical height, I just changed the vertical height setting (V option) during the ApplyMeshUVN command - the default value of 1 yielded the exaggerated version, applying a value of 0.2 gives the smoother version.

license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text: I designed this 84mm fpv quadcopter as a trainer. It uses DYS BE1104 7500kv Brushless Motors, EMAX F3 FEMTO Flight Controller (running BetaFlight), DYS 2" 5 Blade Propellers - Set of 4 (2x CW, 2x CCW), Lumenier Mini BLHeli_S 10A 4-in-1 OPTO ESC DSHOT, FrSky XM SBUS Micro Receiver without telemetry and FX798T Camera Combo with Dipole Whip Antenna 5.8GHz 37CH 25mW. Most of these items came from GetFPV. I made all of my connections on the bottom of the flight controller to allow for quick and easy replacement of the flight controller mounting/prop guard section. I was able to use 6mm ss socket head screws for mounting the props and the motors. The camera has a bit of single sided foam tape on the top and bottom to help dampen vibration. The FrSky XM Receiver bracket is mounted to the center of the bottom of the camera bracket with a small drop of super glue. I printed this quad in PLA, and it is holding up nicely. This micro requires the same knowledge to build as a 250mm fpv quad. Actually, it requires finer soldering skills due to the 16X16mm size of the flight controller. It is tiny. Right now I am using a Lumenier 400mah 2S 50C battery and a Tattu 450mah 3S 45C. Both of these batteries came from GetFPV. The 84mm is like a rocket on the 3S. Also, I just added an .stl file for the Femto F3 flight controller mount without the prop guards for those of you who don't want them and added a heavier duty version of the X frame (v1.1). This has turned into one of my favorite quads! Have fun!

title: 10W High Power LED Battery powered Torch

description.text:
This is a very bright LED!
I run this 12V LED with only 9V, so that the heat is not so high and the consumption remains acceptable.
The cooling fins get warm in about 55 degrees Celsius / 131F and I do not need a fan and the plastic (PETG) does not soften (measured in 22 degrees Celsius space).

You need the following parts:

  • 10W LED (10 pieces 2 €)
  • heat sink (1 €)
  • Voltage Regulator (5 pieces 1,50 €)
  • LiPo Charger (10 pieces 1,50 €)
  • Battery 18650 (5 €)
  • Protection Sircuit (5 pieces 1 €)
  • Switch (10 pieces 1,50 €)

So all together, it does not cost much and you have lots of parts left for future projects ;)

I glued an aluminum bracket with 20x30x20mm between the LED and the heat sink, so I have a bit more grip.
The switch is screwed with two 2mm screws, but you could also just glue it.
The lid on the back is simply glued on with superglue.

The consumption is 0,4A directly on the battery when the regulator is set to 9V. With a 3400mA battery you would have to get 8,5h runtime. The LED does NOT become darker because the Voltage Regulator always holds 9V. When the battery is dead, the LED will start blinking.
Charging takes a long time, but it is not a problem.

Have fun building!
